iStock Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Kampala - &nbsp;A gold refinery primarily owned by a Belgian investor has been launched in Uganda amid concerns about the source of its minerals.The African Gold Refinery, worth $15m and the first of its kind in East Africa, has drawn the attention of activists who are concerned that dirty minerals from conflict-prone countries in the region will be among its raw materials.The refinery has been operating since 2014, but was officially inaugurated on Monday at a ceremony attended by Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni.The value of gold exports from Uganda has been rising in recent years, though not much is mined locally.George Boden of Global Witness said at least some of Uganda's gold exports are likely to be from Democratic Republic of Congo and South Sudan, raising concerns about conflict minerals.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.